knowledge_graph.title: Cinnamon
knowledge_graph.description: Cinnamon is a spice obtained from the inner bark of several tree species from the genus Cinnamomum. Cinnamon is used mainly as an aromatic condiment and flavouring additive in a wide variety of cuisines, sweet and savoury dishes, breakfast cereals, snack foods, bagels, teas, hot chocolate and traditional foods.

related_questions.question: What are the benefits of cinnamon?
related_questions.snippet: Cinnamon is an effective anti-inflammatory. Researchers tested the phytochemicals found in cinnamon and discovered antioxidant and anti-inflammatory effects. related_questions.question: Does cinnamon burn belly fat?

Cinnamon can also improve body metabolism, targeting the fat deposited in the abdominal area.

buttons.subtitle: What Is Cinnamon Good For?
buttons.title: Cinnamon: A Multifaceted Medicinal Plant - PMC - NCBI
buttons.snippet: In addition to being used as a spice and flavoring agent, cinnamon is also added to flavor chewing gums due to its mouth refreshing effects and ability to remove bad breath [13]. Cinnamon can also improve the health of the colon, thereby reducing the risk of colon cancer [14].

buttons.subtitle: Which Form Of Cinnamon Is Best For Health
buttons.title: Health Benefits of Ceylon Cinnamon - WebMD
buttons.snippet: All types of cinnamon contain a compound known as coumarin, which is known to be harmful in large amounts. Ceylon cinnamon has much less coumarin than cassia cinnamon. If you are concerned about coumarin, Ceylon cinnamon is a safer option for your spice rack.

buttons.subtitle: How Much Cinnamon Should You Take Daily
buttons.title: 10 Evidence-Based Health Benefits of Cinnamon - Healthline
buttons.snippet: Numerous human studies have confirmed the beneficial effects of cinnamon, showing that it can lower fasting blood sugar levels and improve hemoglobin A1c, a marker of long-term blood sugar control ( 23 , 24 ). The effective dose is typically 1–6 g, or around 0.5–2 tsp. of cinnamon per day ( 24 ).

buttons.subtitle: What Is The Healthiest Cinnamon
buttons.title: Ceylon vs. Cassia: Not All Cinnamon Is Created Equal - MedicineNet
buttons.snippet: Ceylon cinnamon is the healthier of the two types and the more expensive. It has a milder flavor than cassia cinnamon because it contains less cinnamaldehyde, the essential oil compound that gives cinnamon its distinctive taste and flavor.

buttons.subtitle: How To Eat Cinnamon
buttons.title: Cinnamon: Health Benefits and Side Effects - WebMD
buttons.snippet: Mix some cinnamon powder with sugar, then sprinkle it on buttered toast. It can also be a delicious topping for sweet potatoes. Or you can use it to spice up plain yogurt or your morning coffee. Simply combine 2 teaspoons of cinnamon into 1 cup of granulated sugar and keep it in a sealed container.

buttons.snippet: Saigon cinnamon is usually considered strongest in flavor and routinely has the highest volatile oil content. Korintje comes in second place for high volatile oil content, with a smoother finish and less bite compared to Saigon and cassia.

buttons.subtitle: How Much Sugar Is In Cinnamon?
buttons.title: How to Make Cinnamon Sugar—And 5 Ways to Use It | Epicurious
buttons.snippet: The perfect cinnamon-sugar ratio is 1 cup granulated sugar to 1 Tbsp. cinnamon, plus, and you can quote me on this, a pinch of kosher salt. In a small bowl, mix the sugar, cinnamon, and salt together with a whisk or a spoon. With a total time of just 30 seconds, it really doesn't get any easier than this.

buttons.subtitle: What Does Cinnamon Taste Like
buttons.title: Spice Hunting: Cinnamon - Serious Eats
buttons.snippet: Known as canela in Mexico, Ceylon cinnamon, or "real" cinnamon, C. verum is milder than its brash counterpart cassia. It's far less spicy, and if sampled with expectations of cassia it may disappoint. Its flavor tends toward vanilla: a warm floral note with hints of heat and honeyed fruit.

buttons.subtitle: Types Of Cinnamon
buttons.title: 4 Types of Cinnamon and Their Health Benefits
buttons.snippet: There are four main types of cinnamon: cassia, Ceylon, Saigon, and Korintje. Each has its own flavor profile and chemical composition. Cassia cinnamon is more readily available than Ceylon cinnamon, but it has a higher coumarin content, which can be toxic if consumed in significantly large doses.

buttons.subtitle: Cinnamon Allergies
buttons.title: Cinnamon allergy: Symptoms, diagnosis, and treatment
buttons.snippet: Symptoms of a cinnamon allergy include nausea, stomach pain, and hives. Cinnamon comes from the inner bark of several trees that are native to China, India, and Southeast Asia. It's a popular ingredient in many foods, drinks, and personal care products.
